If the total calorie target is {total} and I have consumed {spent} calories then I have {total}-{spent} = <<{total}-{spent}={total-spent}>>{total-spent} calories left to eat. But due to exercise we add {exc} to {total-spent} reaching {total-spent+exc}.
If each serving of {food} has {cal} calories and I only have {total-spent+exc} calories left to eat, then I can only eat {total-spent+exc}/{cal} of a serving = {Fraction(total+exc-spent, cal)} of a serving
We also know that a {size} {unit} bag of {food} has {n} servings, hence each serving has {size} {unit}/{n} = <<{size}/{n}={size//n}>>{size//n} {unit}
If I can only eat {Fraction(total+exc-spent, cal)} of a serving, then I can eat only {size//n} * {Fraction(total+exc-spent, cal)} = {size//n}*{Fraction(total+exc-spent, cal)} = {size//n * Fraction(total-spent+exc, cal)} {unit}
#### {size//n * Fraction(total+exc-spent, cal)}
